✅ What is file‑based routing?
File‑based routing is a routing mechanism where the folder and file structure of your project automatically determines the application’s routes (URLs)—without writing explicit routing configuration.
This is a core feature of Next.js.

🔹 How File‑Based Routing Works in Next.js
In Next.js, each file represents a route.
Example (Pages Router)

pages/
 ├── index.js        →  /
 ├── about.js        →  /about
 ├── blog/
 │    └── post.js    →  /blog/post
✅ No Route definitions
✅ No route mapping files
✅ The URL structure mirrors the file structure

Example (App Router – Modern Next.js)

app/
 ├── page.js         →  /
 ├── about/
 │    └── page.js    →  /about
📌 Routes are created using folders and page.js.

🔹 Dynamic Routes (Data‑Driven URLs)
Using square brackets ([]):
pages/product/[id].js
This matches:
	• /product/101
	• /product/202
The value id is available as a route parameter.

🔹 Nested Routes

pages/dashboard/settings.js
→ /dashboard/settings
✅ Nested folders create nested URLs automatically.

🔹 Catch‑All Routes
pages/docs/[...slug].js
Matches:
	• /docs/intro
	• /docs/guide/setup
Used for documentation or deeply nested content.

🔹 Benefits of File‑Based Routing
✅ No manual routing configuration
✅ Cleaner, predictable URLs
✅ Better developer productivity
✅ Built‑in support for dynamic and nested routes
✅ SEO‑friendly architecture

🧠 Interview‑Ready Answer (30 Seconds)
	File‑based routing means routes are automatically created based on the project’s folder and file structure.
	In Next.js, each file inside the pages or app directory becomes a route, removing the need for manual route configuration and making routing simple, scalable, and SEO‑friendly.

